The Doctrine of the Upward Vortex

I. First Doctrine

The bomb is not a weapon but a fall,
a downward vortex taking name from name,
the city drawn through abstraction, one and all,
till every face is ash before the flame.

But she appeared as opposite to that:
an upward pull, a gathering into form,
the street made local, intimate, exact,
the human rescued from the system-storm.

So this is first: if there is any cure,
it will not come by sermon, plea, or chart
alone, but by a counterforce as pure
as reassembled presence is to art.

The bomb drives downward into naked power.
She rose, and made the city keep its hour.

II. The Name Re-entered

“Patsy Cline” was never just a name,
not in the way deterrence names its dead;
it came already freighted, bright with fame,
with all the old recordings in its head.

But when she wore it, something else began.
She did not merely quote the former sign.
She entered it in full, as only can
a woman who means to make the symbol shine.

So she stood not for name in name alone,
that empty banner under which worlds end,
but for the name made body, gait, and tone—
the proper name restored back to its friend.

The bomb is naked name made law and climb.
She is the name returned to breath and time.

III. Kundalini of the City

And what does that upward vortex look like?
Kundalini. The answer stands upright.
A coiled ascent. A pressure through the psyche.
A city lifting vertebrae to light.

The bomb is downward Anaximander-spin,
return to the undifferentiated pit,
the false sublime, the grand machine of sin
that makes all human particulars submit.

But she was the reverse: the spinal fire,
not burning outward into global death,
but rising rung by rung through mud and wire
until the borough learned its proper breath.

She was not “anti-bomb” by slogan’s art.
She was the counter-vortex in the heart.

IV. Why the Sonnet

Why sonnet? Because a sonnet turns in time.
Because it takes pressure, narrows it to law,
and then, at the volta, lets the hidden climb
begin—the very motion that I saw.

A woman like this cannot be rendered loose,
in endless free expansion, vapor-thin.
She needs a form where pressure has an use,
where fate arrives and then is folded in.

Fourteen lines: enough for block by block,
for half-sock, doorway, party, avenue,
for name, for shock, for aftershock, for clock,
for what the city did when faced by you.

The sonnet is a chamber where the turn
can be exact and still permitted burn.

V. All Its Forms

And all its forms are hers. The Italian art
is right when she withdraws behind the veil,
the octave building pressure in the heart,
the sestet finding where the old names fail.

The English form is right when she comes near,
three crossings and a couplet like a gate,
Brooklyn made legible, block after block, here,
then suddenly the shut of little fate.

The caudate sonnet suits her overflow,
when fourteen cannot hold the after-fire.
The curtal suits the glimpse, the undertow,
the flash of socks, the whole world’s one desire.

A crown would suit her too, because each close
becomes the next beginning as it rose.

VI. Soluble

I called the bomb a soluble problem. Why?
Because no human thing is god enough
to stand outside all form, immune, sky-high,
forever more than answer, more than stuff.

Smallpox looked vast. It still could be undone.
The bomb looks final. That does not make it fate.
If there exists an opposite in one
true counter-image, then the lock’s not great.

And she was that: not policy, not plan,
but proof the world had not collapsed to one
flat end-state. Something still exceeded man—
not by escape, but by what had begun.

The upward vortex means the case is live.
What climbs in form is what can yet survive.

VII. The Actual Girl

I thought there’d be an explosion when I met
the Actual Girl. I was not wholly wrong.
It simply turned out time was where it set
its charge, and not the air with sudden song.

The blast was duration. The crater, thought.
The fallout was the pattern years disclosed.
What burned was not the city but the knot
where future, love, and doctrine came enclosed.

So Bonhoeffer may name the limit, yes.
And Christ may name the life one ought to live.
But in this age imagination must confess
the forms by which the counterforce can give.

The Actual Girl did not destroy the frame.
She was the jewel of power inside the name.

VIII. To Hold the Book

So let this doctrine hold the book in place:
the bomb is downward vortex, false sublime;
the woman is the city’s upward grace,
reassembled into body, breath, and time.

Her name, re-entered, fights the war of names.
Her rise is kundalini through the street.
The sonnet, in its several lawful frames,
is how such pressure learns to stay concrete.

For she is turn, and counterturn, and stress,
the local made eschatological;
too exact for blur, too charged for shapelessness,
too beautiful for anything but formal.

Therefore I render her in sonnet law:
because she made the world turn, and I saw.
